// Auto-generated from presets - all question data embedded for offline use
// Generated: [{'name': '第一章 口语交际', 'description': 'Section 1 Oral Communication — 完成对话、访谈问答、场景交际', 'is_exam_paper': False, 'paper_year': '', 'questions': [{'type': 'single', 'content': '[口语交际·医疗场景]\nDoctor: "The test results are back. Your cholesterol levels are slightly elevated."\nPatient: "______ What should I do?"', 'option_a': "That's great news!", 'option_b': 'Oh, I see.', 'option_c': "I don't believe you.", 'option_d': 'Why are you telling me this?', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "医患沟通中，患者应对医生的诊断表示接收和理解。'I see'表达了理解，然后问'What should I do?'引出后续治疗建议。这是典型的'理解→求询'交际模式。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[口语交际·面试场景]\nInterviewer: "Why do you want to leave your current position?"\nCandidate: "______"', 'option_a': 'My boss is terrible and I hate everyone there.', 'option_b': "I'm looking for new challenges and opportunities to grow professionally.", 'option_c': "They don't pay me enough.", 'option_d': 'I was fired for poor performance.', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "面试中'为何离职'要正面表达——强调对新机会的追求而非对旧工作的抱怨。B展现了职业发展导向的积极态度。A抱怨前任雇主是面试大忌，C过于直白，D自我贬低。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[口语交际·校园场景]\nStudent A: "I\'m thinking of dropping this course. The workload is overwhelming."\nStudent B: "______ Have you talked to the professor about it?"', 'option_a': "Yeah, just give up. It's easier.", 'option_b': 'I understand. It is a tough course.', 'option_c': "You're just lazy.", 'option_d': 'Nobody cares about your problems.', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': '校园同伴支持。B先表达理解(I understand, It is a tough course)建立共情，再用问句引导对方寻求帮助。这是有效的同伴沟通策略——先共情，再引导行动。'}]}, {'name': '第二章 词汇选择', 'description': 'Section 2 Vocabulary — 近义词替换、语境选词、固定搭配', 'is_exam_paper': False, 'paper_year': '', 'questions': [{'type': 'single', 'content': "[词汇·近义词替换]\nThe professor's lectures were so _____ that attendance dropped by half by mid-semester.", 'option_a': 'engaging', 'option_b': 'monotonous', 'option_c': 'inspiring', 'option_d': 'stimulating', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': 'monotonous=单调的、乏味的。attendance dropped by half说明课程不受欢迎，应选贬义词。engaging/inspiring/stimulating均为褒义词(吸引人的/鼓舞人心的/刺激的)，与出勤率下降矛盾。'}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[词汇·近义词替换]\nThe two companies decided to _____ on the development of the new technology.', 'option_a': 'compete', 'option_b': 'collaborate', 'option_c': 'separate', 'option_d': 'withdraw', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "collaborate=合作。两家公司共同开发新技术应为'合作'。compete=竞争(共同开发不可能竞争)，separate=分开，withdraw=退出。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[词汇·近义词替换]\nThe medication is _____ in treating the symptoms, though it does not cure the disease.', 'option_a': 'ineffective', 'option_b': 'efficacious', 'option_c': 'harmful', 'option_d': 'useless', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "efficacious=有效的(尤指药物)。though表示让步——虽不能治愈但能'有效'缓解症状。ineffective/useless与treating矛盾，harmful为贬义。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[词汇·语境选词]\nThe new evidence _____ the hypothesis that the decline was caused by climate change rather than human activity.', 'option_a': 'contradicted', 'option_b': 'corroborated', 'option_c': 'undermined', 'option_d': 'refuted', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "corroborate=证实。新证据'证实'了假设。contradict=与...矛盾，undermine=削弱，refute=驳斥，均为否定该假设的词。句中rather than提示两种解释的对比，corroborated表明证据支持其中一种。"}]}, {'name': '第三章 阅读理解', 'description': 'Section 3 Reading Comprehension — 主旨大意、细节定位、推理判断、词义猜测', 'is_exam_paper': False, 'paper_year': '', 'questions': [{'type': 'single', 'content': "[阅读理解·科技类]\nArtificial intelligence systems have achieved remarkable feats in recent years, from defeating world champions in complex board games to generating convincing human-like text. However, these systems remain fundamentally limited in ways that are not always apparent. They lack common-sense reasoning, cannot truly understand the content they process, and are prone to making errors that no human would make — such as confidently stating false information as fact. Researchers distinguish between 'narrow AI,' which excels at specific tasks, and 'artificial general intelligence' (AGI), which would possess the flexible, general-purpose intelligence of humans. Most experts agree that AGI remains decades away, if it is achievable at all.\n\nQuestion: What is the main idea of this passage?", 'option_a': 'AI has already achieved human-level intelligence in all domains.', 'option_b': 'AI has impressive capabilities but also fundamental limitations that distinguish it from human intelligence.', 'option_c': 'AI is completely useless and should be abandoned.', 'option_d': 'AGI will be achieved within the next year.', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "主旨大意题。文章结构：先承认AI成就(However前)，转折后重点论述AI的局限性，最后区分窄AI和AGI。B准确概括了这种'肯定+但是'的平衡观点。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[阅读理解·科技类 第2题]\n(同上一段)\nQuestion: According to the passage, what is a key limitation of current AI systems?', 'option_a': 'They cannot play board games.', 'option_b': 'They lack common-sense reasoning and may confidently state false information.', 'option_c': 'They are too expensive to develop.', 'option_d': 'They can only be used in academic research.', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': '细节定位题。文中明确列出：lack common-sense reasoning, cannot truly understand content, prone to making errors such as confidently stating false information。'}, {'type': 'single', 'content': "[阅读理解·教育类]\nThe flipped classroom model, in which students watch recorded lectures at home and use class time for active problem-solving, has gained popularity in higher education. Proponents argue that this approach transforms the instructor from a 'sage on the stage' into a 'guide on the side,' enabling more personalized instruction and deeper engagement with course material. However, the model's effectiveness depends heavily on students completing the pre-class work — a requirement that proves challenging for those juggling work, family, and academic responsibilities. Studies have shown mixed results: while some courses have seen significant improvements in student performance, others have found no measurable difference compared to traditional lecture formats.\n\nQuestion: What does the phrase 'sage on the stage' suggest about traditional teaching?", 'option_a': 'The instructor is a wise figure who primarily lectures to passive students.', 'option_b': "The instructor is invisible and doesn't interact with students.", 'option_c': 'Students are the primary speakers in the classroom.', 'option_d': 'Teaching happens outdoors on a stage.', 'correct_answer': 'A', 'explanation': "词义猜测题。'sage on the stage'(台上的圣人)与'guide on the side'(身旁的引导者)形成对比——前者代表传统讲授式教学(教师是台上的智者向被动学生传授知识)，后者代表翻转课堂(教师是旁边的引导者)。"}]}, {'name': '第四章 完形填空', 'description': 'Section 4 Cloze — 语境线索、词汇衔接、语法结构、逻辑推理', 'is_exam_paper': False, 'paper_year': '', 'questions': [{'type': 'single', 'content': '[完形填空·社会生活类]\nIn recent years, there has been a growing awareness of the importance of mental health in the workplace. Employers are increasingly recognizing that employees who are (1)______ stressed or burned out are less productive and more likely to take sick leave. As a result, many organizations have begun implementing wellness programs that include access to counseling services, flexible work (2)______, and mindfulness training. While these initiatives represent a positive step, critics argue that they sometimes serve as a (3)______ for addressing deeper structural issues such as excessive workloads and job insecurity. True workplace well-being, they contend, requires not just individual-level interventions but (4)______ changes to organizational culture and management practices.\n\nQuestion 1:', 'option_a': 'slightly', 'option_b': 'chronically', 'option_c': 'rarely', 'option_d': 'occasionally', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "chronically=长期地、慢性地。语境线索：'less productive and more likely to take sick leave'表明是持续的压力状态。chronically stressed=长期压力(心理学高频搭配)。slightly=轻微地，rarely/occasionally=很少/偶尔，程度不够。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[完形填空·社会生活类 第2题]\nQuestion 2:', 'option_a': 'arrangements', 'option_b': 'salaries', 'option_c': 'contracts', 'option_d': 'deadlines', 'correct_answer': 'A', 'explanation': 'flexible work arrangements=弹性工作安排(HR管理术语)。wellness programs内容包括心理咨询、弹性工作安排、正念训练。salaries=薪酬(并非wellness program的典型内容)，contracts=合同，deadlines=截止日期。'}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[完形填空·社会生活类 第3题]\nQuestion 3:', 'option_a': 'solution', 'option_b': 'substitute', 'option_c': 'complement', 'option_d': 'addition', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': "substitute=替代品。'serve as a substitute for addressing deeper structural issues'——这些项目成了解决深层结构问题的'替代品'(表面功夫而非根本解决)。这是对wellness washing(健康洗白)的批判。solution=解决方案(相反意思)，complement/addition=补充。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[完形填空·社会生活类 第4题]\nQuestion 4:', 'option_a': 'superficial', 'option_b': 'systemic', 'option_c': 'temporary', 'option_d': 'cosmetic', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': 'systemic=系统性的、根本的。not just individual-level interventions but systemic changes——个人层面干预vs.系统性变革的对比。superficial/cosmetic=表面的/粉饰的(与真正需要的改变矛盾)，temporary=临时的。'}]}, {'name': '第五章 短文完成', 'description': 'Section 5 Text Completion — 句段插入、语篇衔接、逻辑顺序', 'is_exam_paper': False, 'paper_year': '', 'questions': [{'type': 'single', 'content': "[短文完成·语篇排序]\nDirections: Arrange the following sentences in logical order.\n\n① Moreover, the skills acquired through reading — critical thinking, empathy, and the ability to sustain focused attention — are increasingly valuable in a world dominated by fragmented digital media.\n② Reading fiction has been shown to offer significant cognitive and emotional benefits.\n③ For instance, a 2013 study published in Science found that reading literary fiction improved participants' performance on tests measuring empathy and social perception.\n\nCorrect order:", 'option_a': '②→③→①', 'option_b': '①→②→③', 'option_c': '③→①→②', 'option_d': '②→①→③', 'correct_answer': 'A', 'explanation': "标准语篇结构：②主题句(提出观点)→③举例论证(For instance引出具体研究)→①递进补充(Moreover引出更广泛的意义)。这是学术写作的经典'总—分—补'三段式。"}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[短文完成·语篇排序]\nDirections: Select the best sentence for the blank.\n\nA. However, this does not mean that face-to-face communication has become obsolete.\nB. The widespread adoption of digital communication tools has transformed how people interact in both professional and personal contexts.\nC. On the contrary, research suggests that in-person meetings remain crucial for building trust and negotiating complex deals.\n\n(1)______ (2)______ (3)______\n\nCorrect order:', 'option_a': 'B→A→C', 'option_b': 'A→B→C', 'option_c': 'C→B→A', 'option_d': 'B→C→A', 'correct_answer': 'A', 'explanation': "B引入主题(数字通信改变人际互动)→A用However转折提出'这不意味着面对面交流过时了'→C用On the contrary进一步论证面对面仍然重要。However→On the contrary的逻辑推进是典型论证链。"}]}, {'name': '第六章 翻译与写作', 'description': 'Section 6 & 7 Translation & Writing — 英译汉、写作思路、段落展开', 'is_exam_paper': False, 'paper_year': '', 'questions': [{'type': 'single', 'content': '[翻译判断]\nChoose the best Chinese translation:\n"The integration of digital technologies into traditional manufacturing processes — often referred to as Industry 4.0 — holds the potential to dramatically improve efficiency while simultaneously reducing environmental impact through optimized resource utilization."', 'option_a': '数字技术与传统制造流程的融合——通常被称为工业4.0——有可能通过优化资源利用，在显著提高效率的同时减少对环境的影响。', 'option_b': '工业4.0就是传统制造业。', 'option_c': '数字技术对制造业没有影响。', 'option_d': '传统制造业不需要数字技术。', 'correct_answer': 'A', 'explanation': 'A完整准确翻译了所有关键信息：Industry 4.0=工业4.0，dramatically improve efficiency=显著提高效率，simultaneously reducing environmental impact=同时减少环境影响，optimized resource utilization=优化资源利用。'}, {'type': 'single', 'content': '[写作·论证方法]\nWhich of the following best demonstrates the use of a counterargument in an essay about the benefits of remote work?', 'option_a': 'Remote work is great because you can work in pajamas.', 'option_b': 'While critics contend that remote work can lead to social isolation and reduced collaboration, studies have shown that well-designed virtual collaboration tools and regular in-person meetups can effectively mitigate these concerns.', 'option_c': "I like working from home. It's nice.", 'option_d': 'Everyone should work remotely all the time, no exceptions.', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'explanation': '学术写作·反证法。B先用While critics contend that...引入对方的反对观点(social isolation, reduced collaboration)作为counterargument，然后用studies have shown that...反驳该观点并给出解决方案。这是标准的counterargument-rebuttal论证结构。'}]}, {'name': '2001年同等学力英语真题', 'is_exam_paper': True, 'paper_year': '2001', 'description': '2001年同等学力人员申请硕士学位英语水平全国统一考试 — 阅读理解+完形填空', 'questions': [{'num': 46, 'content': 'Americans usually consider themselves a friendly people. Their friendships，however，tend to be shorter and more casual than friendships among people from other cultures. It is not uncommon for Americans to have only one close friend during their lifetime，and consider other “friends” to be just social acquaintances. This attitude probably has something to do with American mobility and the fact that Americans do not like to be dependent on other people. They tend to “compartmentalize”（划分）friendships，having“friends at work”，“friends on the softball team”，“family friends”，etc. Because the United States is a highly active society，full of movement and change，people always seem to be on the go. In this highly charged atmosphere，Americans can sometimes seem brusque （无礼的）or impatient. They want to get to knowyou as quickly as possible and then move onto something else. Sometimes，early on，they will ask you questions that you may feel are very personal. No insult is intended；the questions usually grow out of their genuine interest or curiosity，and their impatience to get to the heart of the matter. And the same goes for you. If you do not understand certain American behavior or you want to know more about them，do not hesitate to ask them questions about themselves. Americans are usually eager to explain all about their country or anything“American”in which you may be interested. So much so in fact that you may become tired of listening. It doesn’t matter because Americans tend to be uncomfortable with silence during a conversation. They would rather talk about the weather or the latest sports scores， forexample，than deal with silence. On the other hand，don’t expect Americans to be knowledgeable about international geography or world affairs，unless those subjects directly involve the United States. Because the United States is notsurrounded bymany other nations，someAmericans tend to ignore therest oftheworld.\n\nThegeneral topicofthe passageis . 学苑中心： 学苑教育网络课程：', 'options': {'A': 'American culture B.American society', 'C': 'Americans’activities D. Americans’personality'}, 'passage_num': 2, 'section': 'reading', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'option_a': '', 'option_b': '', 'option_c': '', 'option_d': ''}, {'num': 47, 'content': 'Americans usually consider themselves a friendly people. Their friendships，however，tend to be shorter and more casual than friendships among people from other cultures. It is not uncommon for Americans to have only one close friend during their lifetime，and consider other “friends” to be just social acquaintances. This attitude probably has something to do with American mobility and the fact that Americans do not like to be dependent on other people. They tend to “compartmentalize”（划分）friendships，having“friends at work”，“friends on the softball team”，“family friends”，etc. Because the United States is a highly active society，full of movement and change，people always seem to be on the go. In this highly charged atmosphere，Americans can sometimes seem brusque （无礼的）or impatient. They want to get to knowyou as quickly as possible and then move onto something else. Sometimes，early on，they will ask you questions that you may feel are very personal. No insult is intended；the questions usually grow out of their genuine interest or curiosity，and their impatience to get to the heart of the matter. And the same goes for you. If you do not understand certain American behavior or you want to know more about them，do not hesitate to ask them questions about themselves. Americans are usually eager to explain all about their country or anything“American”in which you may be interested. So much so in fact that you may become tired of listening. It doesn’t matter because Americans tend to be uncomfortable with silence during a conversation. They would rather talk about the weather or the latest sports scores， forexample，than deal with silence. On the other hand，don’t expect Americans to be knowledgeable about international geography or world affairs，unless those subjects directly involve the United States. Because the United States is notsurrounded bymany other nations，someAmericans tend to ignore therest oftheworld.\n\nWhich ofthefollowing statements is NOT TRUE according tothe passage？', 'options': {'A': 'Americans donotliketo depend onother people.', 'B': 'Friendships among Americans tend to becasual.', 'C': 'Americans knowa lotabout international affairs.', 'D': 'Americans always seem to beonthego.'}, 'passage_num': 2, 'section': 'reading', 'correct_answer': 'A', 'option_a': '', 'option_b': '', 'option_c': '', 'option_d': ''}, {'num': 48, 'content': 'Americans usually consider themselves a friendly people. Their friendships，however，tend to be shorter and more casual than friendships among people from other cultures. It is not uncommon for Americans to have only one close friend during their lifetime，and consider other “friends” to be just social acquaintances. This attitude probably has something to do with American mobility and the fact that Americans do not like to be dependent on other people. They tend to “compartmentalize”（划分）friendships，having“friends at work”，“friends on the softball team”，“family friends”，etc. Because the United States is a highly active society，full of movement and change，people always seem to be on the go. In this highly charged atmosphere，Americans can sometimes seem brusque （无礼的）or impatient. They want to get to knowyou as quickly as possible and then move onto something else. Sometimes，early on，they will ask you questions that you may feel are very personal. No insult is intended；the questions usually grow out of their genuine interest or curiosity，and their impatience to get to the heart of the matter. And the same goes for you. If you do not understand certain American behavior or you want to know more about them，do not hesitate to ask them questions about themselves. Americans are usually eager to explain all about their country or anything“American”in which you may be interested. So much so in fact that you may become tired of listening. It doesn’t matter because Americans tend to be uncomfortable with silence during a conversation. They would rather talk about the weather or the latest sports scores， forexample，than deal with silence. On the other hand，don’t expect Americans to be knowledgeable about international geography or world affairs，unless those subjects directly involve the United States. Because the United States is notsurrounded bymany other nations，someAmericans tend to ignore therest oftheworld.\n\nThephrase“highly charged”（Paragraph 2）mostprobably means .', 'options': {'A': 'extremely free B.highly responsible', 'C': 'very cheerful D. fullof mobilityand change'}, 'passage_num': 2, 'section': 'reading', 'correct_answer': 'B', 'option_a': '', 'option_b': '', 'option_c': '', 'option_d': ''}, {'num': 49, 'content': 'Americans usually consider themselves a friendly people. Their friendships，however，tend to be shorter and more casual than friendships among people from other cultures. It is not uncommon for Americans to have only one close friend during their lifetime，and consider other “friends” to be just social acquaintances. This attitude probably has something to do with American mobility and the fact that Americans do not like to be dependent on other people. They tend to “compartmentalize”（划分）friendships，having“friends at work”，“friends on the softball team”，“family friends”，etc. Because the United States is a highly active society，full of movement and change，people always seem to be on the go. In this highly charged atmosphere，Americans can sometimes seem brusque （无礼的）or impatient. They want to get to knowyou as quickly as possible and then move onto something else. Sometimes，early on，they will ask you questions that you may feel are very personal. No insult is intended；the questions usually grow out of their genuine interest or curiosity，and their impatience to get to the heart of the matter. And the same goes for you. If you do not understand certain American behavior or you want to know more about them，do not hesitate to ask them questions about themselves. Americans are usually eager to explain all about their country or anything“American”in which you may be interested. So much so in fact that you may become tired of listening. It doesn’t matter because Americans tend to be uncomfortable with silence during a conversation. They would rather talk about the weather or the latest sports scores， forexample，than deal with silence. On the other hand，don’t expect Americans to be knowledgeable about international geography or world affairs，unless those subjects directly involve the United States. Because the United States is notsurrounded bymany other nations，someAmericans tend to ignore therest oftheworld.\n\nIt can be inferred from thepassagethat .', 'options': {'A': 'Americans want to participate in all kindsof activities', 'B': 'Americans’character isaffected bytheir social and geographical environments', 'C': 'Americans donot knowhowto deal with silence', 'D': 'Curiosity ischaracteristicof Americans'}, 'passage_num': 2, 'section': 'reading', 'correct_answer': 'A', 'option_a': '', 'option_b': '', 'option_c': '', 'option_d': ''}, {'num': 50, 'content': 'Americans usually consider themselves a friendly people. Their friendships，however，tend to be shorter and more casual than friendships among people from other cultures. It is not uncommon for Americans to have only one close friend during their lifetime，and consider other “friends” to be just social acquaintances. This attitude probably has something to do with American mobility and the fact that Americans do not like to be dependent on other people. They tend to “compartmentalize”（划分）friendships，having“friends at work”，“friends on the softball team”，“family friends”，etc. Because the United States is a highly active society，full of movement and change，people always seem to be on the go. In this highly charged atmosphere，Americans can sometimes seem brusque （无礼的）or impatient. They want to get to knowyou as quickly as possible and then move onto something else. Sometimes，early on，they will ask you questions that you may feel are very personal. No insult is intended；the questions usually grow out of their genuine interest or curiosity，and their impatience to get to the heart of the matter. And the same goes for you. If you do not understand certain American behavior or you want to know more about them，do not hesitate to ask them questions about themselves. Americans are usually eager to explain all about their country or anything“American”in which you may be interested. So much so in fact that you may become tired of listening. It doesn’t matter because Americans tend to be uncomfortable with silence during a conversation. They would rather talk about the weather or the latest sports scores， forexample，than deal with silence. On the other hand，don’t expect Americans to be knowledgeable about international geography or world affairs，unless those subjects directly involve the United States. Because the United States is notsurrounded bymany other nations，someAmericans tend to ignore therest oftheworld.\n\nAccording to thepassage，Americans tend to ignore therest of theworld because .', 'options': {'A': 'they are not interested in othercountries', 'B': 'they are too proud of themselves', 'C': 'theircountry does not have many neighboring nations', 'D': 'they are too busyto learn about other countries'}, 'passage_num': 2, 'section': 'reading', 'correct_answer': 'C', 'option_a': '', 'option_b': '', 'option_c': '', 'option_d': ''}, {'num': 51, 'content': 'Want a glimpse of the future of health care？Take a look at the way the various networks of people involved in patient care are being connected to one another，and how this new connectivity isbeing exploited to deliver medicineto thepatient-no matter wherehe orshemay be. Online doctors offering advice based on standardized symptoms are the most obvious example. Increasingly，however，remote diagnosis（telemedicine）will be based onreal physiological data from the actual patient. A group from the University of Kentucky has shown that by using an off-the-shelf（现成的）PDA（personal data assistance）such as a Palm Pilot plus a mobile phone， it is perfectly feasible to transmit a patient’s vital signs over the telephone. With this kind of equipment in a first-aid ki（t 急救包），the cry asking whether there was a doctor in the house could well beathing ofthepast. Other medical technology groups are working on applying telemedicine to rural care. And at least one team wants to use telemedicine as a tool for disaster response—especially after earthquakes. Overall，thetrend is towards providing global access to medical dataand expertise. But there is one problem. Bandwidth is the limiting factor for transmitting complex medical images around the world—CT scans being one of the biggest bandwidth consumers. Communications satellites may be able to cope with the short-term needs during disasters such as earthquakes，wars or famines. But medicine is looking towards both the second-generation Internet andthird-generation mobilephones forthe future ofdistributedmedical intelligence. Doctors have met to discuss computer-based tools for medical diagnosis，training and telemedicine. With the falling price of broadband communications，thenew technologies should usher in（迎来） an era when telemedicine 